Yesterday I walked in the rain through the market to get to my shop, Jawaab, where I help set up my internship. As my family friends explained, the market turns into a free-for-all after rain as people hustle to sell and buy items. Plus the flood causes my host aunt, who doesn’t live in the market, to sit with her makeshift tent where she sells until rain starts again. I ran through little puddles that smelled funny. But for the most part, the calling customers and waving of hands at me and more calling customers was less intimidating as it was not boiling out.

Everyone seems to be preparing for the upcoming wedding of my nanny. It is supposed to last four days, but the only event things are a bit hampered by the rain. Until then, I practice my tigrigna to better perform karaoke in the future, get tired and hungry, drink beer and avoid fulfilling Westeronn (western goals and wants) with nnuna Nanu. I read Amharic books on technology, cultural traditions, and food for my thesis. I thank Hanna’s three month old baby every day for refusing to be handfed. He has strong breath, will sing and wait for four of us to feed him, and he begins to coo right upon waking and before bed every day.

Someday soon I will be finished with my thesis and internship
